text:
46, 48-30, 32-4, 58-62 West Eight Street, south side, between Macdougal Street and Sixth Avenue: shops, grocery store and tenements, movie, night club, and lunch wagon, on one of Greenwich Village's principal streets. 46 West 8th Street replaced an 3-story stable, 52-4 was built around 1927, and the lunch wagon stands on the site of old 56 West 8th Street. See the closer view of 52-4 and 56, taken the same date. Of 58-60-62, only 58 is actually shown here.
May 24, 1933
P.L. Sperr

52-4 and 56 West 8th Street, south side, between Macdougal Street and Sixth Avenue.

52-4 is a rather modernistic structure built about 1927, replacing the two old 3-story houses in the rear of which was Clinton Court. (This part of 8th Street was formerly also known as Clinton Place). The 8th Street Playhouse started out as the Film Guild Cinema, but has changed hands since 1930 and settled down as just a good movie theatre. On the floors above, the Knickerbocker Democrats of the 10th Assembly District will have their headquarters during the municipal election of 1933.

56, a 4-story building standing where the lunch wagon is now shown, was taken down after 1930. In the summer of 1935 a 1-story store will be built on this site.

May 24, 1933.

P. L. Sperr.

181 and 179 MacDougal Street, at and adjoining the S.W. corner of West 8th Street, showing two buildings that are to be demolished and replaced by a business structure. These were built in 1846 and occupied by "Gonfarone's" sometime in the 70's. For further data see the New York Times of May 30, 1937.

May 1, 1937.

P. L. Sperr.

title: Street scenes - Miscellaneous.

text:
MacDougal Alley, east from MacDougal Street; a short dead end thoroughfare extending to but not entering on Fifth Avenue. The small structures shown were stables that have been renovated into studio apartments. In the background are two of the dominant features of this area. That on the left is the apartment hotel, No. 1 Fifth Ave. To the right of center is the towering residential unit, No. 1 University Place.

1939-40

Alexander Alland, photo
